 Nation at a Glance

 Husband can get maintenance too

 Lucknow (PTI): A husband unable to support himself is entitled to maintenance from his earning wife, Allahabad High Court has ruled.

 The Lucknow bench of the court gave the ruling on a petition filed by Santosh Kumar Gupta seeking maintenance from his working wife on the ground that his income was too meagre to enable him to maintain himself. 

 The court ruled that the provision of interim maintenance during proceedings of matrimonial disputes was applicable to both the spouses.

 The bench directed the wife to pay Rs 2,000 a month to Kumar, an employee in the state-owned sick unit Uptron Corporation, which paid him only Rs 1,000 a month. His wife, who works in a bank at a salary of Rs 13,000, had filed a divorce petition in a family court.

 Jail boss in fraud net

 Amritsar (PTI): Three officials of Amritsar 

 central jail, including the superintendent and his deputy, 

 were arrested by the vigilance bureau on the charge of misappropriating 

 jail funds.

 Superintendent captain S.P. Singh, deputy superintendent Avinash Chander and another jail official were arrested after a vigilance team, led by a deputy superintendent, conducted a raid on the central jail on Thursday.

 The team noticed large-scale irregularities when they went through the purchase records of the jail canteen.

 Afroze bail 

 Mumbai (PTI): Bombay High Court granted 

 bail on Thursday to a man convicted by an anti-terror court 

 on the charge of conspiring with al Qaida to attack India, 

 Australia and the UK. Mohammed Afroze was asked to deposit 

 a bond of Rs 1 lakh and report to police every month.

 Farmhouse stick

 New Delhi (PTI): Delhi High Court has 

 took exception to reported non-compliance of its July 6 

 order banning use of farmhouses for events like weddings 

 in violation of the Delhi master plan. The court has asked 

 petitioner Bhrashtachar Virodhi Sangathan to file an affidavit 

 giving details by December 6.

